Lab 4 - Course Catalog

Lab 4 - Course Catalog

Introduction

The objective of this Lab is to for you to demonstrate your understanding of optionals, arrays, dictionaries and List views. We will build a single-view application that presents a fictitious list of Computer Science courses to the user in a List view and permits them to select one or more. We then allow them to see just the selected courses.

You should have completed the study of iOS 14 Getting Started, modules one through four and Gestures in SwiftUI before attempting this assignment.

This program reads a plist file which is provided for you along with the code to read the plist into an array. You can learn more about plist files on https://developer.apple.com. Our plist file contains a dictionary of fictitious CS course names and descriptions. We will use just the course prefix and number and its short description in this app.

The data is to be sorted and presented in a list with the CS course number (such as "CS 1030" in larger type and the short description underneath the course number in a smaller type). The list is scrollable, and the user may tap on one or more entries to select them.

A Toggle switch is placed at the bottom of the screen, and when enabled, the app limits the displayed courses to those previously selected by the user. Two images, a checkmark and a empty square are used to indicated marked courses. Each time a row is tapped, the selection is toggled between off and on.

The app should respond to a change in the switch by switching from the full course catalog to just those previously selected, with the ON position meaning show only selected courses.

When viewing just the selected courses, the selection toggle for each List entry should still work, so that tapping on a course from the selected courses list should cause it to vanish from that list (because it is now not selected and the courses array is a @State variable causing the List view to redraw itself), and that same entry’s checkmark should then be cleared when viewed in the full course catalog mode.

Example live in the simulator

In this example, the user launched the app, selected five random courses, then toggled the Show Only Selected Courses switch a few times.

Build the User Interface

Notice that the main screen consists of a Text view with string "Course Catalog" at the top (with an accessibility label of "title"), a label of "Show Only Selected Courses" at the bottom, and to the right of this label, a Toggle. The toggle or switch should have an accessibility label as shown below. The list in the middle is a List View.

Here is how you define the Toggle with the correct accessibility label, assuming you named your boolean that keep track of the state of the toggle showOnlySelected:

HStack {
    Toggle("Show Only Selected Courses", isOn:  $showOnlySelected)
        .toggleStyle(.button)
        .accessibilityLabel("showOnlySelectedCoursesSwitch")
}.padding(10)

Create an @State boolean variable (I called mine $showOnlySelected, intitialized to false) for the Toggle so that when the Toggle is clicked, the boolean is changed and the view is redrawn.

Write your Course Catalog app

These are the general requirements for the Course Catalog app:

  • The program loads the courses from the supplied plist file and displays them in a List View in sorted order, with the name of the course (e.g. CS 1400) as the title and the short description as the subtitle. This is most easily done once, in an init() function in a class containing the array of courses.

  • When the user taps the Toggle, switch the table view from showing all of the courses to just the courses previously selected. Every item should have its checkmarks showing. When the Toggle is off, show all courses, remembering which were checked.

Specific instructions:

The object coursesDict is a dictionary, with String keys and Dictionaries as values. coursesDict is a global variable, populated by the function loadCSCourses().

If you would like to see an actual app accessing the coursesDict dictionary and producing an example List view, clone https://github.com/tcowan/cs3260coursecalogexample.git. It is sometimes easier to explain something with actual working code. I invite you to run this example app under the Xcode debugger and poke around. Take a look at the comments.

  • Before loading the List View for the first time, the course information should be sorted by the keys.

  • Use a ForEach with a condition that only adds the entry to the list if showOnlySelected is true and the entry is selected. Add all the entries if showOnlySelected is false.

  • Here is code that will display the checked image the same size as in my example above:

Image(systemName: "checkmark.square")
    .resizable()
    .frame(width: 32.0, height: 32.0)
    .accessibilityLabel("ischecked")

The system name for the unchecked image is called "square" and its .accessibilityLabel must be set to "notchecked".

Until further notice, use:

  • .font(.title3) for the course number

  • .font(.subheadline) for the short description

  • .padding(1) for the VSTACK containing all of the above

You make the row in the list tappable by adding a modifier to the HStack (I created my rows in my list as a VStack inside a HStack):

HStack {
    ...blah blah blah
}
.onTapGesture {
    // do whatever you need to do to remember the row is selected/unselected
}
